{# FAQ #}
<section class="py-16">
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4">
    <h2 class="section-heading text-center mb-10">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="space-y-4" id="faq-list">

      <div class="card overflow-hidden faq-item">
        <button class="faq-toggle w-full flex items-center justify-between p-6 text-left" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white pr-4">Which European country has the lowest income tax for tech workers?</span>
          <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-400 shrink-0 faq-icon transition-transform duration-200"></i>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden px-6 pb-6">
          <div class="prose-custom">
            <p>Bulgaria has one of the lowest flat income tax rates in Europe at 10%. However, total tax burden includes social contributions. Switzerland also offers competitive rates that vary by canton, and Poland's 12% first bracket is very favorable for moderate incomes.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card overflow-hidden faq-item">
        <button class="faq-toggle w-full flex items-center justify-between p-6 text-left" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white pr-4">How do social contributions affect my take-home pay in Europe?</span>
          <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-400 shrink-0 faq-icon transition-transform duration-200"></i>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden px-6 pb-6">
          <div class="prose-custom">
            <p>Social contributions (pension, healthcare, unemployment insurance) can add 10-22% on top of income tax. In Germany, employee social contributions are about 20% of gross salary. In the Netherlands, they're largely built into the income tax brackets. In Switzerland, contributions are around 6% of salary. Always factor in both income tax <em>and</em> social contributions when comparing countries.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card overflow-hidden faq-item">
        <button class="faq-toggle w-full flex items-center justify-between p-6 text-left" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white pr-4">Does the 30% ruling in the Netherlands reduce my tax?</span>
          <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-400 shrink-0 faq-icon transition-transform duration-200"></i>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden px-6 pb-6">
          <div class="prose-custom">
            <p>Yes, the Dutch 30% ruling allows qualifying expats to receive 30% of their salary tax-free for up to 5 years, significantly reducing effective tax rates for highly skilled migrants. You must be recruited from abroad, have specific expertise, and meet a minimum salary threshold of &euro;46,107 (or &euro;35,048 if under 30 with an MSc). Learn more in our <a href="/resources/country-guides/netherlands/">Netherlands guide</a>.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card overflow-hidden faq-item">
        <button class="faq-toggle w-full flex items-center justify-between p-6 text-left" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white pr-4">How accurate is this calculator?</span>
          <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-400 shrink-0 faq-icon transition-transform duration-200"></i>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden px-6 pb-6">
          <div class="prose-custom">
            <p>This calculator provides estimates based on standard tax brackets and social contribution rates for 2025/2026. Actual take-home pay varies based on personal circumstances, deductions, credits, municipal tax rates (especially in Sweden, Switzerland, and Denmark), and marital status. Always consult a local tax advisor for precise calculations before making relocation decisions.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card overflow-hidden faq-item">
        <button class="faq-toggle w-full flex items-center justify-between p-6 text-left" aria-expanded="false">
          <span class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white pr-4">What about special tax regimes for expats?</span>
          <i data-lucide="chevron-down" class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-400 shrink-0 faq-icon transition-transform duration-200"></i>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-content hidden px-6 pb-6">
          <div class="prose-custom">
            <p>Several countries offer special tax regimes for incoming expats: the Netherlands 30% ruling, Portugal's NHR (Non-Habitual Resident) regime with a flat 20% rate for qualifying professions, Spain's Beckham Law with a flat 24% for the first &euro;600,000, and Italy's regime offering 70% income tax exemption. These programs have specific eligibility criteria and durations. This calculator currently supports the Netherlands 30% ruling toggle.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</section>

